CONVERSATION TITLE: BNSF Railway Opportunity - Accounting Internship
SUBJECT: BNSF Railway Opportunity - Accounting Internship
CONTENT: Hello!   As a reminder, I'm reaching out to see if you're interested in applying for a position in our Accounting group within Finance department at BNSF Railway.   The BNSF Accounting team is seeking a talented student that want to work in our Payroll Services, Revenue Management, Technology Management as a summer intern. You will be responsible for internal and external reporting, account reconciliations, contract research, maintaining and securing highly sensitive and confidential information, assisting in testing system changes and enhancements, ad-hoc requests, maintaining and building strong customer, employee, and business partner relationships through issue resolution and continuous improvement while maintaining business integrity.   If you aren't familiar with BNSF, we are one of North America‚Äôs leading freight transportation companies. BNSF operates approximately 32,500 route miles of track in 28 states and operates in three Canadian provinces. Check out more about BNSF here: https://www.bnsf.com/about-bnsf/index.page  Salary: $4,125/month   This position is located at our Fort Worth, Texas corporate office and has the potential to be a hybrid position with up to 50% remote work.  If this position sounds interesting to you, please apply at the link below :)  https://jobs.bnsf.com/us/en/job/90826/Accounting-Summer-Intern-2024-Paid-Fort-Worth-TX  If you are not interested in the Accounting internship, but might be interested in other departments, check out our full list of opportunities below:  https://jobs.bnsf.com/us/en/c/college-recruiting-jobs  Thank you! -Katie DeWaters, HR Manager  Katherine E. DeWaters Human Resources Manager - College & EFLS Programs at BNSF Railway

SUBJECT: Speaker Opportunity for WorkWonder Con Jan. 2024
CONTENT: Hi Morgan,  I am working at Bayha Group, an education consulting company and I am currently planning a free networking event with Bayha Group for WorkWonder.  WorkWonder is a paid apprenticeship for high school students. We have worked with historically underrepresented youth between the ages of 15-18. We have worked with over 1,000 youth throughout California over the past 5 years. The convention is going to be held at L.A. River Studios on January 27th, 2024. This networking event is intended to showcase aspects of WorkWonder through youth involvement, small businesses, and keynote speakers, with an estimated 300 attendees. Our attendees will be past and present interns as well as community partners and industry professionals.  We are looking for female speakers for our event and would love to have you to represent females working in tech. The event will require in person attendance but we can cover any travel expenses.  Please let me know if you are interested and I can forward more details about the event or if you have questions!  Bayha Group: https://www.bayhagroup.com/¬†  Work Wonder: https://workwonder.io/

Hi Aaron!!   Ya know, these kind of messages absolutely make my day so thank you for reaching out!  If I were to back in high school (and knew I wanted to be a PM, which was not the case for me üòÇ), here‚Äôs what I‚Äôd do ~  ‚Ä¢ internships can be hard to come by ~ if you do wanna go that route, get yourself a work permit (you can get one as young as 14) ‚Ä¢ start building your own products (if you‚Äôre interested in tech pm, build tech products) - maybe an app, a website, hardware, etc  ‚Ä¢ ‚¨ÜÔ∏è for product inspo ~ listen to peoples problems. PM is all about building products that actually satisfy a need a solve a problem. ‚Ä¢ get really really good at your communication skills. This is probably THE most important part of being a PM, you have to ‚Äúspeak everyone‚Äôs language‚Äù I.e designers, engineers, business people, executives ~ to do this, put yourself out there and start going to networking events and form new relationships!  ‚Ä¢ try your hand at building your own startup (doesn‚Äôt necessarily have to be tech); when you‚Äôre in HS, you don‚Äôt have tuition or bills to worry about. So then is as good of a time to to take risks!! I did this in hs, and ultimately my startup failed but it left me with a great project to put on my resume!!  I hope this helps! Lmk if I can be of help to you in the future!  Best, Morgan

SUBJECT: Workforce Analyst role at WDW
CONTENT: Hi Morgan,  I hope you are doing well!  I have been a connection and a follower for a bit of time and have an opportunity to share to gauge your interest. SUBJECT: Interview with NPR about Grace Hopper conference?
CONTENT: Hi Morgan! I'm a reporter with NPR News, based in Washington D.C..  We're working on a story about how many men showed up to this year's Grace Hopper conference and I came across your LinkedIn post on the topic.  I'm wondering if you'd be interested in doing a short phone interview today to share more about what you saw and experienced?  Let me know if you're interested and we can go from there. Feel free to text/call if it's easier at 951.473.4866 or email at eolson@npr.org. Thanks!

Dear Morgan,  Golden Capital Markets (GCM) helps business owners discover their growth and exit potential by introducing them to world-class advisory services. GCM can also introduce you to its resource affiliate, bringing middle-market businesses like yours to over 35,000+ potential buyers. If you are considering an exit or want to explore proven growth strategies before you sell, let's have a conversation. SUBJECT: Looking to increase efficiency?
CONTENT: Hi Morgan! Thanks for connecting!  I have taken a look at your profile, and I'm really impressed by your practice and the measures you've taken to scale your business.  Quick question: Do you have well-documented processes and procedures and if so, are they being followed?  The reason I ask is as a leading process consultant for more than 20 years now, I've seen similar companies to yours struggling with onboarding and training new hires, experiencing a lack of consistency in different parts of the business, as well as having vital knowledge reside only in the heads of some key employees...  That's why I help fast-growing companies achieve consistency and increased efficiency by documenting their processes and procedures and ensuring that they are followed by all so they can grow and scale.  So if you happen to be thinking about how you can increase efficiency, train better and mitigate risk (or even if you're just curious), I'd love to connect with you for a free Process Mapping Session where I will:  - Map the core processes that need to be documented so that there is clarity and a reliable roadmap to how the business best operates - Identify the order of priority in which processes need to be documented - Provide a custom plan on how to get the processes followed by all  If there is a fit, we can talk about how I can help. If not, you will have gained new ideas that will help you achieve your business goals with increased efficiency.  I guarantee this will be the best 30 minutes you spend on improving your business this week.  Are you open to a call to explore? --Adi.

Hi Luke,  First of all, let me just say this is so wholesome that you‚Äôre reaching out to figure out how you can help your daughter pursue her interests üòÅ  Question #1: there really isn‚Äôt a good answer to that question, as every company has a very wide tech stack (different languages for different use cases), but I‚Äôd highly recommend she start with Python. It‚Äôs a nice learning curve and incredibly versatile (essential to machine learning, data science, automation). To prepare for college curriculum, she should learn C/C++, but try not to start her with that. Unlike python, it has a significant learning curve, and scares a lot of kids away from CS. If she‚Äôs interested in building apps or websites, I‚Äôd highly recommend she learn some low-code development tools like Microsoft Power Apps, Bubble.io, Adalo, etc. It‚Äôs more important for her to learn CS principles that will carry across languages rather than hone in on one language specifically.   Question #2: build real things, write code, debug, write technical documentation, and communicate well. Often, people forget that being a software engineer isn‚Äôt just passing a coding interview, it‚Äôs building real stuff (apps, platforms, features, etc.). Debugging is also a huge part of a SWE‚Äôs job that is often overlooked. I really want to emphasize the last 2. Most SWEs do not possess the last two skills yet they‚Äôre SO important. Make sure your daughter gets familiar with learning how to explain what she‚Äôs built and articulate without using a bunch of jargon/big words.   Question #3: both are incredibly useful; BUT, speaking as someone who‚Äôs in the industry, there‚Äôs still a stigma around bootcamps vs degrees. In my opinion, bootcamps produce more effective SWEs than college does. HOWEVER, getting a college degree will allow your daughter to have more job opportunities as most jobs still require a degree. Plus, with a CS degree, if she finds out Software Engienering isn‚Äôt quite her thing, she could be able to pivot to other tech jobs like Product Management, Data Science/Analytics, Business Analysis, etc. A CS bachelor‚Äôs degree is incredibly versatile and it opens up more doors than bootcamps do.

SUBJECT: Seeking Financial stability After a Career Gap
CONTENT: Dear Morgan Young,   I trust this message finds you well. I hope it's not appropriate to reach out in this manner, but I am facing a challenging situation that has led me to consider reentering the workforce after a career gap of almost three years. Your insight and guidance have always been valuable to me, and I am hoping to seek your advice on this matter.   Over the past few years, I have faced significant financial pressure due to my family responsibilities, unexpected expenses. While I took a  break from my career during this time, it has become increasingly evident that returning to work is necessary to stabilize my financial situation.   I have spent these past years honing my skills, staying updated with industry trends, to ensure that I can contribute effectively to any organization I join. My career gap allowed me to develop a newfound appreciation for the importance of financial stability, which fuels my motivation to reenter the workforce with even greater dedication.   I understand that rejoining the workforce after a career gap presents its unique challenges, and I would greatly appreciate your guidance on how to navigate this transition successfully. Any advice, job search strategies, or referrals you could provide be invaluable to me as I embark on this journey.   If you have some time to spare for a conversation, I would be extremely grateful. Yours mentorship has always meant a lot to me, and I believe your insights will be instrumental in my pursuit of financial stability and career reintegration.   Thank you for considering my request, and I look forward to your response.   Warm regards,    Monika Jena
I would suggest trying a product management bootcamp like Product School
I see! I‚Äôm just unsure of where to move forward in regards of my roadmap then because of the internship struggle.

It *can* stand for product manager, program manager, project manager, and portfolio manager. Some of them are interchangeable but generally it goes like this   1. Program manager - manages program initiatives that probably have multiple products 2. Product manager - focusing on owning one product or even certain features of a product 3. Project manager - managing tasks that may be involved with a product, but might not 4. Portfolio manager - managing a portfolio, this could be a portfolio of clients, products, program initiatives, or projects  To answer your original question, personally, I don‚Äôt think your minor in management, alone, is enough to qualify for a full-time role; it could for an internship, but it looks like you‚Äôve graduated (?), so you likely wouldn‚Äôt be able to qualify for most internships.

Try for PM roles in HealthTech! My boyfriend has a degree in public health (also his intention throughout undergrad) and he now works in private wealth management, but one of his specialties is healthcare & medical securities.   If you go for healthtech, your biology & management background will make you an already strong candidate, but I would get some experience in tech, i.e. building/designing products, learning some coding, brushing up on technical PM interviews.   As far as roadmap moving forward, if you do choose to take more classes, definitely apply for internships, if not, apply for full-time APM roles. I would highly suggest writing a cover letter that explains your story and shows how your unique background will make you ideal for pm!

That first question, I can confidently answer. No. No matter what field you pick, you will not learn the skills you need in college. There's a few exceptions, example at my school, we're a heavily data science and machine learning-focused school. So you could possibly attain the skills that way. But in general, you will learn what you need to know (especially as a full stack) through side projects, internships, and on the job. I'd recommend finding any classes in your school that *utilize* the languages of full-stack i.e. HTML, CSS, JavaScript, Python, etc. If your school doesn't offer those, get certified in full-stack or those languages by Udemy, Coursera, those type of sites.

SUBJECT: Are you seeing GenZ engage LinkedIn?
CONTENT: Morgan -¬† I enjoy the actionable career content you serve up to LinkedIn and admire your hustling.¬†  I'm an embedded payments lead, formerly of PYPL and Klarna, and late last year my fintech colleagues began reaching out as they networked to a new role. My ready response was, ‚Äòcheck out my LinkedIn, I‚Äôm happy to make intros.‚Äô  But that just put my freshly-wounded friends into an endless scroll of my connections.  That‚Äôs when I started exploring how to bring LinkedIn data to life for easy shareability of my professional reach.  It took a bit, due to LinkedIn‚Äôs walled garden lacking in APIs, but yeahshare is a free web app which quickly delivers a shareable record of where in the world you reach, how many threads into a company you possess, who you message most, and what type of roles make up your network.  In helping others with a yeahshare record, you also gain insights into the LinkedIn network you‚Äôve worked hard to build.  I‚Äôm sharing my own yeahshare record as a visual aid and I‚Äôd love for you to try it out yourself. I'm also interested in better determining if career development on LinkedIn is mission critical for GenZ. Let's connect if you see the value in doing so,  https://app.yeahshare.com/share/37722a32-f714-4c1e-b223-07a7c652424b  Thank you Nicholas

I‚Äôm not sure if you follow her or read her content, but my friend & fellow creator, Jahnavi Shah, had a very similar experience as an int‚Äôl MEM student at Cornell. When I asked her about it, she had essentially applied to probably 1.5x to 2x more internships than I did and received 1/2 the interviews I did. From her experience, we pretty much completely chalked it up to the fact that she needed sponsorship. Unfortunately, that checkbox really limits your prospects as a lot of companies are really unwilling to sponsor, *specifically* for interns because they‚Äôre such short-term hires.   Honestly, having looked at your resume and your profile, I don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs a lack of experience or academic credentials. It‚Äôs really just a numbers game of finding what employers are open to potential future sponsorship. You could also do some research on sites like Glassdoor & TeamBlind to get some more insights on companies that are more int‚Äôl student-friendly.  If you‚Äôre just looking towards the short-term, I would look at startups. No guarantee those will convert to FTE‚Äôs but they can give you a solution in the short-term to at least help with your tuition dependency. Highly recommend looking at Wellfound.com & WorkAtAStartup.com.   I hope this helps and I wish you the best of luck in your journey!!

Yeah, absolutely! So I‚Äôm 20, and a junior in college currently, so I started college in 2020. I did my first internship in 2021, when there really was no other option than remote work. I liked remote work at first because I liked not having someone ‚Äúlooking over my shoulder.‚Äù But I felt really isolated and lonely which totally makes sense because I‚Äôm super extroverted. Plus, I had a hard time creating work life balance when I was working at home. I needed to separate my home space and my work space.  So after it started to become more acceptable to go in public but with masks, I started working from coffee shops. I loved it because I ended up meeting other remote workers and they became my friends. One of the reasons I prefer this over going into work to socialize, is because everyone I meet is different (different company, background, industry, etc). Plus, I went into my office for 3 weeks last year, and while it was fun, i was way less productive in person than remote üòÇ Plus, I hated commuting.   Overall, I really like remote working because ultimately, it allows me to be more productive (no commute, more focus by being by myself), it allows me to actually do my job (I live in Reno, NV and my office is in Burbank, CA), it gives me a much more flexible schedule, and I enjoy going to co-working spaces to get my dose of socialization.

SUBJECT: RE:  Posting..Why Gen Zers are motivated by Pay
CONTENT: Hello Morgan, I read your posting and wanted to respond privately so as to not come across as grandstanding.  Like all posts that I read, there are both accuracies and inaccuracies in your posting.¬† You are spot on in terms of the cost of living.¬† The cost of housing and higher education has spiralled out of control to the point that home ownership is out of reach for more Americans now than ever.¬† And likely you are the first generation that will not be more financially well-off than the prior generations.¬†¬†  There were several words that you used that are unhealthy and dangerous.¬† They are "Expect" and "Exploited".¬† As my dad told me, you need to uplevel to "Preferences", because anytime you quote "Expect" something, you are setting yourself up for disappointment.¬† Also bear in mind that before you write some of the grievances, keep in mind there are individuals out there who have been there along with you.¬† I for one, did not get promoted to a "Manager" until 11 years into my career, but that did not slow me down and I semi-retired at age 54 three years ago.  The other word you used was "exploited".¬† Morgan, if you are not happy with a job, then quit the job and either find another one or go into business for yourself.¬† And I can tell you that going into business for yourself is not easier.¬†¬†  Much of what I see wrong these days is the overuse and over reliance on technology, and that includes social media where people can freely spew out their stream of consciousness without having to pay anything.¬† Like I said, some of what you wrote is spot on but some of it is not accurate and frankly, we have experienced it as well.  Just keep that in mind  Rob Kasof

SUBJECT: thoughts, love your recent post
CONTENT: I love your insights and willingness to share them! I think late/end stage capitalism; the growing awareness of the rise of fascism and shaky state of democracies, world-wide; and super toxic patriarchal patterns in communication, algorithms, hiring practices, corporate culture‚Ä¶everything (!), has an enormous, weathering impact on everyone, but perhaps particularly the younger workforce. Your generation sees how your worth and work is valued (or not) at the same time you struggle to discover your own self worth and what kind of work you would actually like to do. This applies to every generation but you didn‚Äôt get handed out any blinders in school. Nor is there any sort of chutes and ladders. I know minimum wage is rarely discussed on LI but it astounds me to see how few are aware of just what mw would be if it had kept up with the cost of living from the 1970‚Äôs to now. This is meaningful! Support systems for higher wage earners (indeed HNW ppl are greatly supported by me workers) is a huge and systemic factor.  Most young people/immigrants/marginalized/entry level workers start working on a (national) minimum wage and/or for tips. As we experience the (seemingly invisible or scoffed at) hard work that is paid so little/nothing as to be impossible to sustain living, the vital impact of TIME must be factored. Young people, all people ask themselves, ‚ÄúIs this worth it? Is this worth my time, exhaustion, my life? Is this the hill I die on?‚Äù The difference between young generations and others is choice. Young people in this country have been raised to believe the concept of Democracy means choice and so they (rightfully so) expect and even demand it. The rest of us struggle. We struggle with feeling and experiencing we have no choice (family, debt, age, issues of self worth and work ethic, so many, many impactful reasons) Your willingness to stand out from the crowd on LinkedIn to discuss these issues is, I think, SO IMPORTANT. The sea of willfully obtuse or toxic ‚Äòsplainers who cannot see your explorations versus their own ‚Äújournaling via LI‚Äù (are they actually considering how hateful and superior they sound? Go to FB for that, guys) is something I don‚Äôt envy you. But you‚Äôre tough, smart, and hopefully have lots of great support who cares for you. Count me among them. ‚ù§Ô∏è Sorry so long. Who knows if you read this, but just know (older) ppl get your messages, too. Kristin

Yes Deshay! Love that for you ü´∂ Some advice:   1. Just start. It‚Äôs not gonna be perfect. It‚Äôs not gonna be pretty. Your content will get better as you do it more and more and learn what resonates with your audience.   2. Keep a content bank or backlog. Consistency is key with any social media but ESPECIALLY LinkedIn. Start with a pace you can sustain (for example 1x per week, 2x per week, etc.), and keep your ideas in a content bank so you never run out of content.  3. Figure out your content creation workflow as soon as possible. This is just a standardized ‚Äúprocess‚Äù to create content. I didn‚Äôt have one at first and it made it really difficult to output high quality content consistently.   4. Don‚Äôt focus on vanity metrics. Focus on impact. If I had focused on likes or follower growth in my first year, I wouldn‚Äôt have kept going,.

SUBJECT: The Grandpa Simpson of Google Ads
CONTENT: Hi Morgan. I'm Josh Barsch and generally I hate sending messages through LinkedIn, but I'm on my way out of the industry so I hope you'll forgive me for a couple of sentences worthy of your time and possibly make you giggle if I'm lucky. Not that I LOOK this old (just nod and agree please), but I founded the first SEM agency in the world back in 2001 and helped developed the entire discipline over the last 20 years. But I'm tired of the grind, honestly, and I'd like to transition into consulting/advising other agencies that'd find value in someone who's been doing Google Adwords longer than anyone currently at Google Adwords has been doing Google Adwords. (I know I know, it's called "Google Ads" now, but old habits die hard).  Why don't I just sell the agency? Well, I never really built it up to any sellable size, because when I had my daughter back in 2004, I was sitting at my desk holding her and realized I could never handle having to leave her behind every day to go to work. So that very day, I promised my daughter (in my mind, of course....she was probably drooling on me or pooping in her diaper at that moment) that no matter what, I'd never grow the company to the point where I couldn't stay home with her 99% of the time. And I kept that promise to her, and my two sons that came along later, and basically stuck to referral clients.  Never hired a salesperson in 20 years. My small staff and I agreed that giving up growing into a big-dog agency was worth it if it meant we got to spend every moment with our kids as they grew up.  But now my kids are older, and honestly, they don't want me hanging around so much anymore. So here I am pivoting in my career a bit. I've never enjoyed self-promotion (odd, right, given our profession?), but it's a fact that I'm what you might call an elder statesman, institutional memory, or what have you, of the Google/Facebook advertising world. I pioneered the use of separate, specific landing pages for digital ads, before "landing pages" were even a named thing. It's also true I have more experience with Google Ads than anyone currently at Google; I've found myself educating our Google reps on the history of the product for the last 10 years.  There's 100 more stories like this in my knapsack, but cutting to the chase here, I'm looking for other agencies who would find value in my 20 years of knowledge -- namely, to retain me as a consultant for my 20 years of knowing what works, what pitfalls are out there, and most of all, how to spend client money wisely and profitably. I don't want any full-time gigs or to hands-on manage anything -- I just want to be a cheerful and helpful resource to your team, even if it's just for a few hours per month or even per year. I'm fooling around with a price point of $5,000 per year for 50 hours of any kind of work you'd like me to have a hand in -- training, sales support, strategy, implementation, anything you like. When I do one-off consulting my rate is $250/hour, so that's less than half my usual rate.  But I'm just spitballin' here. If you think you'd have a use for a 20-year exec who's seen and done everything you can do in the Google Ads ecosystem (and most of Facebook's, too), just drop me a note and let's see what we can work out. Most folks find me fun to work with and a generally enjoyable guy, and they learn a ton from me. If you're not sure, just stash me here in your inbox, because like I said, there will be no annoying follow-up emails after this one -- I promised I'd exit gracefully and I'm gonna do just that. I hope you find me worthy of your consideration, but if not, I wish you the best and more future success than you've ever dreamed of! Have a great day!

On LinkedIn: ¬† Former Palm colleague, @Nash Raghavan was my goto a while back, now another Palm colleague, @Dai Khong is probably someone I would ping for LinkedIn issues. BUT, I think I¬¥m too far gone for that. ¬† I lived about 2 blocks away from the LinkedIn headquarters in Sunnyvale, I watched them build it (and later my home burned in a fire and I landed in Vegas!). I starting using Linkedin when they launched (which was on May 5, 2003, I joined August 11), I think it is a great ‚Äúlive business card,‚Äù especially with the ease people like me could switch jobs back then, but it has become a write-first marketing facebook platform which I call a ‚Äúnecessary evil,‚Äú and more and more people I deal with agree. Clearly a substantial minority, but I think there are better ways than LinkedIn. ¬† If you share my comments with LinkedIn, great, but I am already headed for the exit. ¬† Thanks again, great meeting you! -dh ¬† ps I had a chat with Josh in our usual carpool chat back up to C.Hills, including the things I spoke about with you, especially the bigger picture of education and our STEM focus here‚Ä¶ fwiw.

SUBJECT: UC Berkeley SWE x Startup Spring Pitching Event
CONTENT: Hi Morgan,  My name is Sarika, and I‚Äôm a member of the Startup Spring Corporate Committee for UC Berkeley‚Äôs Society of Women Engineers.   SWE is a nonprofit organization striving to support the next generation of women engineers by providing professional development resources and networking opportunities, hosting socials to connect engineers to others in their area of study, leading outreach programs for local K-12 students, and encouraging equity and inclusion within STEM.   UC Berkeley SWE‚Äôs Corporate Startup Spring sector organizes events throughout the semester to promote entrepreneurship and engineering. Events include startup info sessions and professional development workshops, designed to help students learn more about careers in startups, entrepreneurship, and surrounding fields.   We‚Äôre planning an hour-long in-person event on-campus this semester, designed for students to learn more about content marketing in the startup space and network, while learning how to pitch an idea! It would be valuable for students to hear from a startup that has recently (and successfully) navigated through the space, while gaining insight into current trends and tips.   The presentation portion will be followed by a Shark Tank-inspired activity for students to practice pitching their own startup ideas. While the interactive activity will be led by SWE, we would like to invite you to present about personal branding / how to successfully pitch to VCs for this first portion of the event as well, to offer pointers and help us structure it as a workshop!   Would you be interested in collaborating with us on this? We‚Äôre open to any suggestions you may have, and look forward to hearing back! We are hoping to host this event on either April 11 or 13 evening but are flexible with timing.   Please let us know about your availability and any contacts that we can reach out to in order to get more information or provide any necessary details! We hope to hear from you soon and thank you for your time!   Best, Sarika Pasumarthy UC Berkeley SWE  Startup Spring Committee

Hey Autumn! ¬† Thank you so much for reaching out and thank you for the compliment¬† üòÑ Also, if you ever see me again in person, please say hi! I promise I don't bite üòÇ I love meeting people from LinkedIn IRL! ¬† I get most of professional attire from SHEIN (shein.com) and depending on the sub-brand, I'm typically an XS-S (0-2). $400-$500 is a really great sized budget, you can get a lot from that.¬† ¬† The key to maximizing your wardrobe budget is getting staples you can mix & match. So here's what I'd recommend: ¬† 1) blacks & whites are a MUST. get yourself a black blazer/sports jacket & a white one 2) depending on if you're a skirt girl or a pants girl (I do both, depending on the level of comfort I desire), get a black pencil skirt, white slacks/pants, black slacks/pants.¬† 2a) depending on the vibe of your work, you could also get away with wearing nice, tailored black jeans or black yoga pants 3) shoes: nude & black shoes ~ get a nude pair of flats and heels + black pair of flats & heels. as far as style - go with pumps, either closed or peep-toe  4) accessories: a little goes a long way - get a black and a white watch (they're super cheap on SHEIN)¬†  5) once you've gotten your staples (assuming you buy them thru SHEIN), pick accent colors - mine are pink & red. i.e. I wear a pink top under my white blazer and shorts 6) comfort tips ~ two big pet peeves - #1 - I hate it when my tights fall down, so get black, nude, or white sports shorts to wear over your tights and under your skirt. #2 - skirts riding up. Pick a skirt with a small slit so that your skirt can adjust while you walk, instead of riding up.

Hi Morgan, Love your posts around pay/salary transparency, but I feel that something overall is missing from the whole conversation, what is the ideal solution.  In my opinion, the pay ranges should be regional, this is likely the root cause of so many having a big range.  Salary averages should also be broken down by factors, such as experience and/or performance.  Since companies also use third party data providers, they should update their data points to also include these factors.  I am 100% for transparency.  Gary

Hey Jenn! I‚Äôm so happy for you! Here‚Äôs a couple of tips:  - the phone screening is very casual. It‚Äôs mostly just eligibility questions to make sure you can fulfill the role if you are selected for it.  - I‚Äôve seen a lot of Disney interns succeed with the STAR method for answering questions (try this article -> https://www.themuse.com/advice/star-interview-method) - know your ‚Äúdisney‚Äù moment. Ask yourself and prepare to tell a story around the question ‚Äúwhat was the moment/memory where you went from being a disney *fan* to wanting to be a part of the magic / cast member?‚Äù  - make sure your passion for the brand comes through. As this is disney, they get a ton of applicants that could be qualified for the job. So what they look for is pure, genuine passion for the Disney brand - Disney‚Äôs whole thing is that ‚Äúwe are storytellers.‚Äù Try to frame your answers in the form of stories. No matter what kind of position you‚Äôre going for, you have to have a certain level of storytelling abilities.

Hi Manjot! So for how I got the Disney role specifically, I started in Software Engineering -> IT Service Management -> Product Management. It can be tough to go for a PM internship since just a CS background definitely doesn't give you everything you need for a PM internship. You can definitely apply for PM internships, but here's a few things you can do to strengthen your PM background/resume ¬† ‚û° add a business minor or take a few business classes, specifically in marketing, project management, and management ‚û° try some product management certifications on udemy, coursera, linkedin learning etc. ‚û° try getting into an "exploratory" or rotational program like Microsoft Explore (SWE + PM) ‚û° the BEST one: create a website, app, or basic software and "manage the product" through the product lifecycle, create a product roadmap, timeline, GANTT chart, product vision & strategy etc. ¬† As for highlighting your current experiences, there are a few key skills you'll need to prove through projects or experience: communication, user interviews/research/experience/design, product competitive analysis, "stakeholder management", project management, and a strong Computer Science background.  ¬† I hope you find this helpful!

Okay so here's a few tips for specifically landing an internship at Disney:  1. watch my youtube video that i will release later this week because all of those tips will be applicable¬†üòÇ 2. some divisions/teams in Disney are more privy to hiring freshmen. In my org (Enterprise Technology) alone, they hired 3 freshmen last year including myself. 3. attend Disney Coffeehouses. This is a really good way to show interest in the company and to meet with recruiters face-to-face.¬† 4. become very familiar with the business areas of Disney and what they do. ex: DPEP, DMED, Disney Streaming, Corporate, the content production studios (Marvel, Pixar, Animation, 21st century fox) 5. figure out your "Disney moment." Something that Disney recruiters and hiring managers are trained to look for is true, genuine passion for the Disney brand. you can portray this passion through a "disney moment" - a moment in your life where you went from being a Disney fan to wanting to be a magic maker

CONVERSATION TITLE: Liberty Mutual's 2022 Women in Technology Summit
SUBJECT: Liberty Mutual's 2022 Women in Technology Summit
CONTENT: Hi Morgan!   I saw your profile on LinkedIn and thought you could be a great fit for Liberty Mutual's fifth-annual Women in Technology Summit! Our Women in Technology Summit is a two-day, half-day program taking place virtually this year on Thursday, June 23rd and Friday, June 24th that allows participants to be amongst the first to interview for our Summer 2023 TechStart Internship positions! The attached flyer provides more information as well as other details highlighted below.   What is it?  The Liberty Mutual WIT Summit is an immersive two-day program that empowers, motivates, and celebrates women and non-binary individuals, pursuing a career path in technology. Participants will have the opportunity to learn more about Liberty Mutual's TechStart Summer Internship Program and will be guaranteed to interview for a spot in the 2023 intern class.   To be eligible, you must:  ‚Ä¢ Be a current, full-time, undergraduate student identifying as female or non-binary in your freshman or sophomore year  ‚Ä¢ Be working towards a bachelor‚Äôs degree in Computer Science, Computer Engineering, Informatics, Software Engineering, or other related technical programs ‚Ä¢ Possess strong technical, analytical, communication, & organizational skills   If interested, I would definitely encourage you to apply at the link here: https://jobs.libertymutualgroup.com/job/14783514/2022-women-in-technology-summit-remote/.   Please let me know if you have any questions!   Best,  Taryn  Taryn Beatty Campus Recruiter at Liberty Mutual Insurance

SUBJECT: 2022 Find Your Future Forum
CONTENT: Hi Morgan,  Want to learn how to sell yourself on your resume? Not sure how to prepare for an interview? Want to improve your financial literacy? BlackRock is hosting an educational program for college sophomores called Find Your Future Forum! We welcome students of all majors and disciplines to apply. We are seeking talented sophomores across any major or discipline who self-identify as female, Black or African American, Hispanic or Latino, Native American, LGBTQ+ and/or disabled, and have an expected graduation date between August 2023 and July 2024.  How do I apply? Check out the link here for more details: https://careers.blackrock.com/students#find-your-future-forum  When is the deadline? Monday, March 14th @ 8:00AM EST  Are you interested in learning further from me? Feel free to ask me any questions. Otherwise, I look forward to seeing your application!  Best Wishes,  Mikala Bush, M.S. Associate, Campus Recruiter at BlackRock

I also wanted to say I'm sorry if I wasn't as comforting as needed, I understand how being an Asian American is difficult, we have to find middle ground between culture, condescension & discipline from parents; and also find a way to fit into it all. You got this, you're a smart and hard working person and don't be too hard on yourself. Sontag isn't the only thing either. It just one competition you can do. What matters is your drive and your ability to continue pushing no matter the obstacle. There have been contestants that don't get into Sontag and try other competitions and win. Some don't look for external sources for funding at all and still develop their business. And then some that win Sontag and don't even bring their business to market. But all of that is outside your business, and you don't need external validation to know you're doing right. Keep working, stay driven, and never lose sight of your vision.

Hello Morgan,¬†  So I'm going to send what I had initially wrote, basically the same things we talked about. But thank you for coming in and speaking with us. It's amazing how much initiative and forethought you clearly show in your efforts. I know it's hard. Share your story, and show how much heart and emotion you have put into this. I think it would be good to show your backstory, why this means a lot to you, analyze the competition, and do an internal estimation for how much work, finances and cultivation you need to reach your end goal. Also think about it from the judges perspective too. They want to see that they're selecting business that can grow, not ideas that need help establishing a product or service.¬† ----------------------------- Thank you for your patience. We had about 25 teams to go through, so I'm sorry for the delay. The biggest take away I saw from your abstract was that it was hard to interpret the inherent value proposition. I think the presentation was great, and it had amazing organization. It's clear you understand the complexity of your topic and that the value is there. But I think it would come across much clearer if you had quantified information of how much this would benefit your target market.
Property Prospector

So I am actually in a more product management-like role for Disney, but I will say you learn more about the relevant skills for any company on the job. Most of what they teach you in school is just to give you a foundation. For example, most schools generally teach C, C++, Python, and Java. But you'll end up learning more industry-relevant stuff like Go, React, SQL, etc. on the job.¬†  To my knowledge, Disney actually doesn't do technical interviews for intern positions. For full-time positions, they do, but not interns. But in my opinion, LeetCode is great for prep, and HackerRank is worth checking out too! CONTENT: I just posted the below to our CryptoFemmes group, but wanted to make sure everyone here sees it.  _________________  I just bought $5000 worth of tokens for the NFT Marketplace, GhostMarket, and here is why...  Earlier this year, I found and fell in love with GhostMarket.io, which runs on Phantasma, a PoS layer-1 blockchain with built-in NFT functionality. I imagined how great it would be to have a women-owned and operated NFT marketplace to showcase female creators. So, I began working on creating one, and this is still my goal.  Recently, though, I found out that it would be possible to invest in GhostMarket. So, I decided to buy 50,000 tokens out of the supply of 100,000,000 at the private sale price of 10¬¢ per token.   At the current price, it only takes $100,000 to buy 1% of all the tokens. I cannot say whether purchasing a share of GhostMarket is a good investment or not, but I think it would be nice if it had significant female ownership.  Here is why I think that GhostMarket is such a great NFT marketplace. GhostMarket is cross-blockchain compatible. Users can already mint, buy and sell NFTs on three blockchains; Phantasma, Binance Smart Chain, and Polygon. Minting NFTs on Phantasma costs less than $1, and the transaction fees for buying, selling, and transferring NFTs on Phantasma are tiny. Besides ETH, GhostMarket supports 14 other cryptocurrencies for buying and selling NFTs. So, by far, GhostMarket is the most widely accessible NFT marketplace. Plus, in my opinion, it also has the most advanced features of any NFT marketplace.  $5000 is the preferred minimum investment. I'm not sure how flexible that is, but if you only have a small amount to spend, you can always buy some SOUL on KuCoin. SOUL is the stakeable governance token for the Phantasma blockchain that GhostMarket began on.  The GhostMarket token private sale is almost finished. So, anyone interested in investing, contact me soon, and I will explain how.   The KYC process is easy, and citizens of most countries, including the United States, can participate.  GhostMarket Website: https://ghostmarket.io

TO: Di P.,Stela Suils Cuesta Shihab (She/Her/Ella/Ela),Asia Larkin,Haley Larkin ‚ìã üå±,Michelle Staton,Linda Lee,Bettinna  üê≤,Jenna Phillips,Diksha Sharma ,Myrna Figueroa,Sunita Parbhu,Christine Fahey,Leah Katherine Hill,Stephanie So,Alexandra Dohi,LinkedIn Member,Dikra Djerafi,Myrtle A.,Kathleen Marshall,Anne Somanas,LinkedIn Member,Eve Halimi,Laura Medley,El√©onore Blanc ,Naomi Oba,Amna Usman Chaudhry,Anna Kramer,Pavan Kaur,Debbie N.,Muskan Kalra,Laura Nori,Aheli Raychaudhuri ‚≠ï,Rhea Acocos,Mary Wallace,Morgan Young,Elisa Alvarez,LinkedIn Member,Megan Louise,Lisa Fosdick,Sterling Schuyler,kalpana singh
CONTENT: Having it be for female creators will allow us to focus on helping women get their wallets and get set up. I also think it will seem less threatening for women wanting to get involved in NFTs. The blockchain, crypto, and NFTs spaces are filled with mostly men. So, I don't think having something special for women is a bad thing.  I know that around 2% of babies are born intersex. Plus, far more people are gender fluid than people realize. I want us to focus on doing this by women and for women though. After we successfully launch our NFT market, if anyone wants to do another NFT market for the LGBTQ+ community for pride-related art, I'm sure we can put a group together for that.  Verifying identity isn't ideal, but we should do it to protect creators from imposters trying to sell work that isn't theirs ‚Äì and so buyers can trust that they are buying from the actual creator.   Creators can become verified artists Ghostmarket.io, but verification isn't required. For NiftyFemmes, I think we should only have verified artists. This is done on curated NFT markets like superrare.com, and that matches better for what we want to do.  I imagine it as being open to all women,  with curated sections and all creators verified.  What makes our NFT market unique is that it will be launched by women and be for women. I doubt that GhostMarket would want to help us just duplicate GhostMarket. So far, everyone at Phantasma has been very supportive of the idea we presented. So, I think it's better we stick with the original plan of by women and for women.   We can link NiftyFemmes to GhostMarket.io. That way, visitors can easily find NFTs created by everyone, including men and anyone in the LGBTQ+ community. Financially this isn't the best business decision, but it will mean that we are making a thoughtful effort to promote everyone regardless of gender or gender identification.   I want us to have a token called FEM. The FEM token will represent a portion of ownership of the NiftyFemmes NFT Market and be used for determining one's share in the earnings.   We can give a certain number of FEM tokens to creators for getting set up and becoming verified, minting, and selling their first NFT.  We can also set things up so that some FEM tokens go to creators every time they sell an NFT.   I think that the NFTs in NiftyFemmes should be only sold for SOUL, KCAL, and FEM. That way, we will have a 100% eco-friendly and carbon-neutral NFT market,  Because the NFTs will be on the Phantasma blockchain, and all the sales will be for tokens on the Phantasma blockchain, which is 100% eco-friendly and carbon-neutral.

TO: Di P.,Stela Suils Cuesta Shihab (She/Her/Ella/Ela),Asia Larkin,Haley Larkin ‚ìã üå±,Linda Lee,Bettinna  üê≤,Jenna Phillips,Diksha Sharma ,Myrna Figueroa,Sunita Parbhu,Christine Fahey,Leah Katherine Hill,Stephanie So,Alexandra Dohi,LinkedIn Member,Dikra Djerafi,Myrtle A.,Kathleen Marshall,Anne Somanas,LinkedIn Member,Eve Halimi,Laura Medley,El√©onore Blanc ,Naomi Oba,Amna Usman Chaudhry,Anna Kramer,Pavan Kaur,Debbie N.,Muskan Kalra,Laura Nori,Charlene Ocon,Aheli Raychaudhuri ‚≠ï,Rhea Acocos,Mary Wallace,Morgan Young,Elisa Alvarez,LinkedIn Member,Megan Louise,Lisa Fosdick,Sterling Schuyler,kalpana singh
CONTENT: Firstly, there are not insignificant numbers of women who are naturally higher testosterone than is typically regarded as "normal", me being one of them. There are also many of each sex that are born with the chromosomes of the other but under all other criteria, even chemically, fit into their born sex. My biology teacher used to have their students test their chromosomes to illustrate how varied our sex chromosomes really are, but had to stop due to the students freaking out because their chromosomes don't align with their presented identity and genetalia. Then you throw in the ~10% of people who are born intersex. There are much deeper nuances to the discussion than the media would like to share. Science has presented studies that show individuals on hormone therapy lose the advantage of Testosterone after 12 months. Now perhaps we need to study this more to determine exactly when this transformation occurs for typical cases and follow that guidance, but we also need to account for all of those grey areas I mentioned above. Do we disqualify based on chromosomes? Testosterone heavy females? Lots to unpack here.  For our NFT marketplace, Yes, absolutely we want to make this a space by women, for women, but do we want to completely exclude men from joining? Or could we give women a leg up with lesser/no fees where the men who sign up are paying a "blue tax" to subsidize the women's fees or our women elevating causes? How could we even restrict it only to women? What would those restrictions look like? Would they submit their drivers licenses? That is not only a pain to administer (drivers licenses are protected information in the business world and would require much higher security protocols) it would also bar a large number of trans women who through the beurocracy of laws in each jurisdiction are unable to change their sex on their documents. What about those born female who are transitioning to men? When do they become too manly and ineligible? Have them submit pictures of themselves so we can be the arbiters of who is "passing enough"? That is obviously problematic and I wouldn't want to work at a company that has that position title. I don't see any viable way to gatekeep the service. Please share if ya'll have any ideas.   Do we allow men to use the service, but only promote women? Would we even have enough women wanting and able to mint NFTs to ensure the long term viability of the project? We already discussed having a portion of the fees go towards womens empowerment and elevation... should only women be having to fund this? I would love to have men pay for a larger portion of this, but again, what is that bright line that would determine who is a man or woman?  There are ways to design the system which would benefit women without the full out exclusion of near half of the world. Plus we have a chance to be creative and set up a precedent for how to balance the scales in an equitable way. All of this needs to be thought about in a much deeper way. Things are not so black and white.

CONTENT: That's somewhat off-topic, Camila, but it is similar to something that will eventually come up for the NFT market we are doing.  I want to live in a world that treats everyone fairly, that includes the LGBTQ+ community. So, it's something that I've been thinking about, knowing that it's a topic we will eventually need to discuss.  I feel that that in contact sports, trans-women playing can be unfair. It also presents some danger because of genetic size and strength differences. I don't think with art that there is any similar concern, but I think it comes down to honesty. If we open participation up to trans-women, I feel like they should somehow identify themselves as female-identifying males.  There has been discussion of whether trans women should participate in pageants intended for female contestants. I've thought about this and can see both sides. Then I  looked at the Miss International Queen application for their beauty pageant for transgender women, and it has this requirement on the form:  "Birth Certificate (If your passport states you as Female, please upload your birth certificate mentioning your gender as Male)"  I think it's because they rightfully feel that it would be unfair and not honest for women born as genetic females to compete against trans-women.  I don't like anyone needing to label themselves if they don't want to, but I also don't think it's something that's okay to hide from potential buyers.  I haven't made up my mind about whether we should include men who identify as female, or not. I do feel though that it's dishonest to allow men who identify as female to not reveal that about themselves.

TO: Di P.,Stela Suils Cuesta Shihab (She/Her/Ella/Ela),Asia Larkin,Haley Larkin ‚ìã üå±,Michelle Staton,Linda Lee,Bettinna  üê≤,Jenna Phillips,Diksha Sharma ,Myrna Figueroa,Sunita Parbhu,Christine Fahey,Leah Katherine Hill,Stephanie So,Alexandra Dohi,LinkedIn Member,Dikra Djerafi,Myrtle A.,Kathleen Marshall,Anne Somanas,LinkedIn Member,Eve Halimi,Laura Medley,El√©onore Blanc ,Naomi Oba,Amna Usman Chaudhry,Anna Kramer,Pavan Kaur,Debbie N.,Muskan Kalra,Laura Nori,Aheli Raychaudhuri ‚≠ï,Rhea Acocos,Mary Wallace,Morgan Young,Elisa Alvarez,LinkedIn Member,Megan Louise,Lisa Fosdick,Sterling Schuyler,kalpana singh
CONTENT: I should have a Zoom link for the By Women for Women NFT Market discussion with Phantasma soon.  The plan is currently for 8pm EST (UTC-5) which pretty much works well for all of our time zones except for British Summer Time. I believe there it will be midnight when the meeting starts.   Also, SOUL is at the lowest price level that I ever bought for myself.   https://trade.kucoin.com/SOUL-BTC  There is a pretty big buy wall that will probably keep it from dropping any lower. Nothing is for sure, but that's my non-financial advisor guess.  I have 5 Soul Master wallets, which is 250,000 SOUL. It took me about 1 day to acquire the 50,000 SOUL needed for each Soul Master. I mainly used hidden limit orders in front of larger visible orders, either my own or someone else's. That was the best way to get the order filled without driving the price up.  You don't need to be a Soul Master to earn a decent reward from staking SOUL, but the staking rewards are best for Soul Masters. When you stake SOUL, it only locks the ability to unstake it for 1 day. The staking is non-custodial, so you have complete control of the SOUL in your wallet with your Private Key.   The annual APR for a Soul Master is pretty good. Typically between 10-18%, not including the value of a Smart-NFT Crown received every 90 days. When that is factored in, the annual APR is typically in the 20-30% range. Plus, if you decide to leave the Smart-NFT Crown in your wallet instead of selling it, it increases the KCAL token reward SOUL gets by 5%.   https://ghostdevs.com  I'm encouraging other women to buy SOUL because I would like us to own a large share of the Phantasma blockchain and then work together to grow it from a small-cap blockchain to a large-cap.  Women missed the opportunity to own a large share of Bitcoin, Ethereum, and most other large-cap cryptocurrencies. So, I believe that the best shot we have at acquiring a large amount of ownership in a popular blockchain is to invest in one with a small market cap and then help it grow. I like Phantasma for this because the market cap is tiny, but it's an excellent, fully functional blockchain that already has significant projects launching on it. Plus, Phantasma is committed to being eco-friendly and carbon neutral.  If we own a large share of Phantasma and make it a female-friendly blockchain, then together, I really believe that we can grow it into becoming a significant platform.  So, why own SOUL? Because if we are going to launch a women-owned and operated NFT market for women creators and eventually other blockchain projects on the Phantasma blockchain, we should benefit from helping to grow Phantasma.   Also, right now, if you own SOUL, you can stake it and earn KCAL. If you stake 50,000 SOUL, then you earn KCAL, SOUL, and Smart-NFT Crown rewards. My idea is if a woman verifies ownership of a wallet that it will receive additional KCAL and SOUL from the projects we launch, plus earn some of our own tokens, together with Smart-NFTs that are just for us.

TO: Di P.,Stela Suils Cuesta Shihab (She/Her/Ella/Ela),Asia Larkin,Haley Larkin ‚ìã üå±,Michelle Staton,Linda Lee,Bettinna  üê≤,Jenna Phillips,Diksha Sharma ,Myrna Figueroa,Sunita Parbhu,Christine Fahey,Leah Katherine Hill,Stephanie So,Alexandra Dohi,LinkedIn Member,Dikra Djerafi,Myrtle A.,Kathleen Marshall,Anne Somanas,LinkedIn Member,Eve Halimi,Laura Medley,El√©onore Blanc ,Naomi Oba,Amna Usman Chaudhry,Anna Kramer,Pavan Kaur,Debbie N.,Muskan Kalra,Laura Nori,Aheli Raychaudhuri ‚≠ï,Rhea Acocos,Mary Wallace,Morgan Young,Elisa Alvarez,LinkedIn Member,Megan Louise,Lisa Fosdick,Sterling Schuyler,kalpana singh
CONTENT: Hi Dawn,  I'm good at bringing people together. I'm also willing to handle discussing things with the Phantasma developers.  The other thing is getting more women to know that we are trying and acquire enough SOUL that a lot of the platform will be owned by women. This is something that I believe we can achieve with a project with this size market cap. After we own enough, we can contribute whatever skills and resources we have to help the Phantasma blockchain become a serious mid-cap or large-cap blockchain.   I'll try my best to get the NFT market built for free or for a reasonable cost. The more of us who want to do this and who are willing to help make it a success, the easier it will be for me to get the developers behind it. I'm also connected to a lot of female developers. So, as we get closer, I'll work more on talking to them.  To acquire a large percentage of ownership for the blockchain, we just need women willing to buy SOUL. Together with three other women, we already own more than 0.5% of all the SOUL tokens, and I personally own half of that. If four of us can own 1/50th of the blockchain, imagine if only a few hundred of us combined acquired on average a similar amount.   Don't buy SOUL at the market price unless it's a small amount, or it will drive the price up for everyone else. Use limit orders and consider using the hidden order feature. Because we want to be able to buy as much as possible now while the price is low. Once everyone is in, who wants to get in, the price going up will be a good thing.   As for positions, I just want this to succeed, and I want everyone to be happy with whatever leadership hierarchy is created. My part is helping make this happen. Once a lot of the blockchain is owned by women, and we have our NFT market then I'm fine letting others run things and helping as needed.

CONTENT: Anything thing to do with blockchain that involves ETH or BTC mostly benefits the men who got involved early on.¬†  Men may have gotten into crypto sooner, but women are better at networking and working together for a good cause.  I love BTC and ETH, but Phantasma is still small enough that women have the ability to own a large share of a great blockchain. Maybe that's too optimistic, but it's better to shoot for the stars and land on the moon.

TO: Di P.,Stela Suils Cuesta Shihab (She/Her/Ella/Ela),Asia Larkin,Haley Larkin ‚ìã üå±,Michelle Staton,Linda Lee,Bettinna  üê≤,Jenna Phillips,Diksha Sharma ,Myrna Figueroa,Sunita Parbhu,Christine Fahey,Leah Katherine Hill,Stephanie So,Alexandra Dohi,LinkedIn Member,Dikra Djerafi,Myrtle A.,Kathleen Marshall,Anne Somanas,LinkedIn Member,Eve Halimi,Laura Medley,El√©onore Blanc ,Naomi Oba,Amna Usman Chaudhry,Anna Kramer,Pavan Kaur,Debbie N.,Muskan Kalra,Laura Nori,Aheli Raychaudhuri ‚≠ï,Rhea Acocos,Mary Wallace,Morgan Young,Elisa Alvarez,LinkedIn Member,Megan Louise,Lisa Fosdick,Sterling Schuyler,kalpana singh
CONTENT: Hi Jen,   Here's my answer to your question about support, involvement, and money:   We will need support and involvement that involves time and effort for starting the women-owned NFT market that will benefit the owners and can be used for helping other women.   Money at this point is totally optional. The money part is just about us investing and encouraging other women to invest in SOUL so women will own a significant share of the platform we will build the NFT market on. I will try and have the NFT market built by the Phantasma developers for free or for a small and very manageable amount of money.   As I see it, the earnings from the NFT market should be split between the ones who are helping to make it successful. I don't have a specific breakdown on how I think the split should work yet. I figure that once we know who's part of getting things going and making it successful, then we can discuss it and vote on what we feel is fair.   I don't see this as a non-profit venture, but I want one of our goals to be helping women with what we create.

TO: Di P.,Stela Suils Cuesta Shihab (She/Her/Ella/Ela),Asia Larkin,Haley Larkin ‚ìã üå±,Michelle Staton,Linda Lee,Bettinna  üê≤,Jenna Phillips,Diksha Sharma ,Myrna Figueroa,Sunita Parbhu,Christine Fahey,Leah Katherine Hill,Stephanie So,Alexandra Dohi,LinkedIn Member,Dikra Djerafi,Myrtle A.,Kathleen Marshall,Anne Somanas,LinkedIn Member,Eve Halimi,Laura Medley,El√©onore Blanc ,Naomi Oba,Amna Usman Chaudhry,Anna Kramer,Pavan Kaur,Debbie N.,Muskan Kalra,Laura Nori,Aheli Raychaudhuri ‚≠ï,Rhea Acocos,Mary Wallace,Morgan Young,Elisa Alvarez,LinkedIn Member,Megan Louise,Lisa Fosdick,Sterling Schuyler,kalpana singh
CONTENT: Lavinia, you asked about the cost to participate. As for the NFT market, the main thing is for us to have enough of us want it. I will try and get it done for free or at a very reasonable cost. So, the NFT market idea is more about us wanting it and being willing to support it, promote it and help it grow.  As for the cost for us to own a large share of Phantasma, we just need to buy SOUL tokens. We don't need to do this for the NFT market. I just think that if we launch a successful market that increases the platform's value, we should benefit from that also.  There is no specific amount of SOUL anyone needs to buy. It's possible to stake as little as 1 SOUL, silly, yes, but possible. Having 10,000 SOUL earns 20 KCAL a day which is enough to mint an NFT on GhostMarket.io. 10,000 SOUL right now would cost a bit more than $2000. The best return comes from being a Soul Master though, which takes 50,000 SOUL. The cost the buy 50,000 SOUL right now is a little over $10,000.  You can check the price and buy SOUL with BTC or ETH on Kucoin.com.  There are approximately 100,000,000 SOUL tokens. Which is similar to the number of ETH tokens. Every 1,000,000 SOUL represents about 1% of the total supply. So, at SOUL's current price, each 1% of Phantasma blockchain ownership costs approximately $200,000. That's 20 Soul Masters that will be earning between 20% and 30% APR in total rewards (KCAL, SOUL & Crown NFTs).  This is my thought on the price and what it could become. It's my opinion, not financial advice. Please do your own research if you are thinking of investing in SOUL to make a profit. My main interest is for women to have a large share of all the SOUL. This will give us a good percentage of the ownership in an excellent blockchain. I'm not trying to get anyone into SOUL who just wants to buy it and flip it. The earnings are good enough to make it worth holding and will be exceptional if the price goes up.  So, here is what I think... SOUL's price, like most altcoins, dropped recently with the dip in Bitcoin's price, but it is still doing okay because it's a great project. As people got scared and sold, others have been buying their SOUL and staking it. So, the percentage staked has risen. During the sell-off, the amount of SOUL that is staked climbed from around 59% to over 63%.  https://ghostdevs.com  So, there are buyers that are taking advantage of the dip. They are buying SOUL and moving it off the exchange into wallets to stake it.  The ROI / YEAR (APR) shown on the GhostDevs website does not include the value of the Smart-NFT Crown that is earned by a Soul Master every 90 days. When that is factored in, the APR jumps up into the 20-30% range. The Crown NFTs can be sold or left in a wallet. If it is left in a wallet, it increases the KCAL earnings by an additional 5%. Meaning that after a year, the wallet earns 20% more KCAL. So, the tokenomics for Phantasma are pretty amazing.  As for the price, since I've been buying SOUL, its price one time jumped to nearly $1. That is almost five times higher than it is now. KCAL's price is about 0.03 USD right now but has been up to $0.10. Even at $1 for SOUL, I think that it could 10x from there... and that's what I think it could easily do. So, if SOUL went up to $10, that's about 50x from where it is now.  The only other project I've advocated for did way more than 50x. In general, I don't talk about what I'm investing in or advocate for projects. I have a relationship with Blockchain Developer and Crypto Fintech Law. Other than that, the one project's token that I did get involved with did incredibly well. And I believe that Phantasma is a better project.  The prices for SOUL and KCAL would have to go down a lot for me to feel like the staking return on SOUL is a poor deal. So, I feel good about investing in SOUL even if the price stays where it is now, and I would still feel okay if it were to drop down to its historically lowest price range.   I'm happy with my decision to buy SOUL because I've considered the logical best and worse case scenarios and concluded that for me that investing in SOUL makes sense.  Again, don't rely on my assessment, do your own research. Personally, I'm comfortable with the quality of Phantasma's blockchain, the tokenomics, and the current price. So, I believe that us working together as a group to acquire a significant percentage of Phantasma is a great idea.

CONTENT: Something else that's good is our NFT Market will not exist as an island. Just like an NFT minted on pretty much any Ethereum NFT market can be sold on OpenSea.io, the same is true for all NFTs minted on any Phantasma NFT Market, they can all be resold on GhostMarket.¬†  The Phantasma developers are also working on interoperability between the Phantasma blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain. This will allow moving NFTs back and forth between the two blockchains.  The main issue with the above is that neither ERC721 or ERC1155 enforce royalties like Phantasma does. So, if a NFT is moved from the Phantasma blockchain to the Ethereum blockchain, then some Ethereum markets may ignore the royalties and not not pay them.¬†  There is a proposals to fix this issue for Ethereum NFTs, but as it is now it's still a problem.  https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-2981

TO: Di P.,Stela Suils Cuesta Shihab (She/Her/Ella/Ela),Asia Larkin,Haley Larkin ‚ìã üå±,Michelle Staton,Linda Lee,Bettinna  üê≤,Jenna Phillips,Diksha Sharma ,Myrna Figueroa,Sunita Parbhu,Christine Fahey,Leah Katherine Hill,Stephanie So,Alexandra Dohi,LinkedIn Member,Dikra Djerafi,Myrtle A.,Kathleen Marshall,Anne Somanas,LinkedIn Member,Eve Halimi,Laura Medley,El√©onore Blanc ,Naomi Oba,Amna Usman Chaudhry,Anna Kramer,Pavan Kaur,Debbie N.,Muskan Kalra,Laura Nori,Aheli Raychaudhuri ‚≠ï,Rhea Acocos,Mary Wallace,Morgan Young,Elisa Alvarez,LinkedIn Member,Megan Louise,Lisa Fosdick,Sterling Schuyler,kalpana singh
CONTENT: Kelsey you commented:  "Super interested! I have a lot of artist girlfriends who want to create NFTs but are feeling overwhelmed, lost and afraid to jump in. This could be the perfect solution"  Here's my response to that:  Women were late getting involved in crypto, so there are a lot more men who have larger amounts of Ethereum to use on Ethereum based NFT markets.¬†  Ethereum NFT markets are super expensive to use. It can cost in the vicinity of $300 to mint, sell and then cash out what you make for selling an NFT. So, giving it a try is expensive and risky for most artists.   Until we have our own NFT market up and running on Phantasma, I suggest you point your girlfriends to GhostMarket.io¬†  GhostMarket is one of the NFT markets already running on Phantasma. It costs less than $1 to mint an NFT and to put the the NFT up for sale costs 0.001 USD, or less.  It currently costs 20 KCAL to mint 1 NFT which is around 0.60 USD. To mint additional NFTs for the same creation at the same time it¬†costs an additional 4 KCAL¬†which is around 0.12 USD. So if someone wanted to ming 20 NFT at one time it would cost less than $3 USD. So it is entirely possible to make a profit selling NFTs for $1 each, or less.¬†  With NFTs you can set a royalty percentage that will be earned on every future resale. Royalties can be set from 0% to 100%, but most artists will set it somewhere between 10% and 20%.¬†  So lets' say an artist makes 1 NFT per day for a year, and ints a maximum quantity of 20, and sells them all for $5 each, with a royalty of 15%. Then in a year they will have spent around $1000 on minting and selling, and will have grossed about $36,500 in sales. For some people that's good money, and for others not so much. That doesn't factor in the earnings from royalties though. By the end of the year other people would own 7300 of the artists NFTs and every resale would be earning 15%. Plus if any of the artist's NFTs resells for significant amount, then the value of all their NFTs would likely go up.¬†  There is no reason an artist has to do the above. They can mint any quantity they want for an NFT, set the asking price at any amount they want, and set the royalties to whatever they want. What I'm pointing out is that just about any artist producing work of almost any value can participate on a NFT market running on Phantasma.

I'm also interested in working together with you and other women to buy up a significant share of the Phantasma SOUL tokens. I've already help buy up more than one percent of all SOUL tokens with a group that the majority of the members are women. So, this isn't just some crazy idea, it's already underway. Hi Jalen,  I'm so glad you've enjoyed my content and thank you for engaging with it! It's comments like yours that give me the encouragement to keep creating content! To answer your questions:  Internship extensions: it really just depends on the company. Some companies actively try to extend their interns and others don't. I actually didn't ask for my extension (although I wanted it). My leaders were very satisfied with my performance and I was contributing a lot to the company so I was asked to stay on another term. Best advice I can give is focus on contributing value and don't be afraid to promote yourself to make sure your value is known.  Balancing school and internship: I was very strategic and I get first priority registration because I'm an honors student. So i arranged my schedule so I only had classes on Monday and Wednesday, and 1 class on Friday. Plus, my internship is now part-time so it's pretty manageable.

Hi Brittany! Nice to meet you, and happy to connect! That's so cool that you worked for the park for seven years, and now you're at Hulu! It's great that you want to network, but I've come to find that the virtual work environment makes it easier to meet even more people! Because of virtual coffee chats, you can talk to anybody from any part of the world! I have plenty of tips for getting coffee chats, and I love helping fellow cast members! So here are the tips:  For meeting others within the Disney umbrella:  Use the resources at your disposal. Ask your manager, co-workers, or mentors if they know anyone in departments you're interested in. Getting an introduction from them to a complete stranger is a lot better than going in cold. Plus, if you get an introduction, there's a 99% chance they'll say yes. Being under the umbrella of TWDC has plenty of perks (including the Disney network), and most cast members are more than happy to sit down for a chat.  Join slack channels like #womenatdisney and make an introduction to the channel. Tell the channel about who you are and if anyone from the departments you're interested in would be willing to have a coffee chat with you.  Outside of Disney:  Send connection invites to people (on LinkedIn) who work at companies you're interested in and include a personalized message/introduction. Including a message will make them way more likely to notice you and accept your request. Once they've accepted, ask if they'd be willing to do a coffee chat. If you ask politely, they'll probably say yes.  For questions, ask people questions about themselves. As humans, we love to talk about ourselves. Listen carefully and find something you have in common with them or something that connects the two of you. This will make you memorable.

Hi Morgan,  Sure! So I would send you a list of eight questions as prompts. We could either talk through them on Zoom or you could respond over email.  When I get your responses I edit them together into a piece attributable to you. I then send it back for your sign-off before I publish.¬† I'd just need a headshot and any other photos you could supply.  You'd probably need to run them past the press people at Disney too as I'd imagine they would be quite strict about messaging. It is all really positive coverage though and you know exactly what will published so hopefully a win-win!  Here is something similar to give you a feel for what we would be trying to end up with: https://www.womanthology.co.uk/being-a-talented-engineer-is-not-determined-by-background-education-and-experience-its-all-about-mindset-attitude-and-impact-bethany-probert-junior-software-engineer-consultant/¬†  Ideally, I'd need to get hold of your responses by next Friday 4th June.  Suggest questions: 1. Please can you tell us about your educational background and career to date? 2. What does your role involve on a day-to-day basis? 3. How has COVID-19 impacted what you do? 4. Why are internships such an important part of academic learning? 5.¬†Why is diversity of thought so important when problem-solving in software engineering?  6. What is your advice to girls and women who are interesting in careers in computer engineering but are unsure where to start? 7. What does International Women in Engineering Day mean to you and why is it so important for us to celebrate it? 8. What is coming up next for you? What are you excited about?   I hope that makes sense? Let me know if you need any more details.  All best wishes,  Fiona

Do you know what level of code you will be writing ?¬† Java, etc ? Morgan my best advice to a CS person is to understand computer science from bottom up. Really learn what a process is (i.e. all the "apps" people code or browers and java servers that are the actual processes). Computer science is elegant. Learn how TCP/IP really works and layer2 (beneath TCP/IP) protocols like ethernet (how all these "apps' communicate via sockets). Know what a socket is and how it connects to the TCP/IP stack.¬†   You didn't ask, sorry. I have interns at Liqid. I train them personally giving tasks from bottom up so whether they program in bash, java, C, etc, they know what is really happening from the OS point of view.¬†  The ones that love it and do well are the ones that understand the foundations, I think.
